<subSubSection lastPageId="55" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,1925,2024]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,308,1925,1950]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">DIAGNOSIS</emphasis>
: The only extant species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Edwards" authorityYear="1925" box="[625,787,1926,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[625,787,1926,1950]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Leptomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[870,878,1941,1955]" fontSize="6" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">4</subScript>
that has foretarsomere I shorter in length than the forefemur, the lateral ocelli placed less than their own diameter from the eye margin (
<figureCitation box="[1130,1215,1964,1988]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–81" captionStartId="95.[151,263,1524,1547]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-60@95.[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 78–81. Leptomorphus morphology. 78–79. Dorsal view of head showing ocelli placement and arrangement. 78. L. tabatius. 79. L. perplexus. 80–81. Dorsal view of scutum. 80. L. fasciculatus showing covering of fine trichia. 81. L. stigmatus showing pattern and lack of setae or trichia." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
), and no dark wing spot (
<figureCitation box="[213,297,2000,2024]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–69" captionStartId="93.[151,263,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,181,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-173@93.[176,1420,181,1791]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 56–69. Leptomorphus wings. 56. L. furcatus paratype male, dorsal. 57. L. gracilis, ventral. 58. L. grjebinei, ventral. 59. L. hyalinus, ventral. 60. L. magnificus, ventral. 61. L. mandelai holotype male, ventral. 62. L. medleri, ventral. 63. L. nebulosus dark form, dorsal. Arrow indicates cell r4 (contains an extra vein in this specimen). 64. L. nebulosus light form, dorsal. 65. L. neivai ventral. 66. L. obscurus ventral. 67. L. ornatus ventral. 68. L. panorpiformis ventral. 69. L. perplexus paratype female, dorsal. Abbreviations: A1, A2 = Anal veins; C = costa; CuA = anterior branch of cubitus; CuP = posterior branch of cubitus; h = humeral crossvein; M1,M2,M4, = branches of the media; r-m = radial-medial crossvein; Rs = radial sector vein; R1, R4, R5 = branches of the radius; Sc = subcosta; sc-r = subcostal-radial crossvein." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,151,2023]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
This species is most easily confused with either the light form of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Matile" authorityYear="1977" box="[935,1077,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulosus">
<emphasis box="[935,1077,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">L. nebulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1093,1175,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–29" captionStartId="88.[151,263,1982,2005]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,183,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-54@88.[151,1436,181,1961]" captionTargetPageId="88" captionText="FIGURES 24–29. Leptomorphus habitus. 24. L. nebulosus, female, dark form. 25. L. nebulosus, male, dark form. 26. L. nebulosus, female, common colour. 27. L. nebulosus, male, light form. 28. L. obscurus, male. 29. L. neivai, male." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) or 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Matile" authorityYear="1977" box="[1222,1375,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnificus">
<emphasis box="[1222,1375,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">L. magnificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 20–23" captionStartId="87.[151,263,1643,1666]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,215,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-41@87.[151,1436,213,1622]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="FIGURES 20–23. Leptomorphus habitus. 20. L. hyalinus, male. 21. L. magnificus, male. 22. L. medleri, male. 23. L. mandelai, holotype male." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). It can be distinguished from the former by the lack of any dark markings on the scutum and the monochromatic antennae (
<figureCitation box="[447,532,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–33" captionStartId="89.[151,263,1758,1781]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,223,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-41@89.[151,1436,217,1737]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURES 30–33. Leptomorphus habitus. 30. L. ornatus, female. 31. L. panorpiformis, male. 32. L. perplexus, paratype female. 33. L. quadrimaculatus, male." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). It differs from the latter species by the yellow head, the sinusoidal R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1311,1319,239,253]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">5</subScript>
wing vein (
<figureCitation box="[159,242,263,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–69" captionStartId="93.[151,263,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,181,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-173@93.[176,1420,181,1791]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 56–69. Leptomorphus wings. 56. L. furcatus paratype male, dorsal. 57. L. gracilis, ventral. 58. L. grjebinei, ventral. 59. L. hyalinus, ventral. 60. L. magnificus, ventral. 61. L. mandelai holotype male, ventral. 62. L. medleri, ventral. 63. L. nebulosus dark form, dorsal. Arrow indicates cell r4 (contains an extra vein in this specimen). 64. L. nebulosus light form, dorsal. 65. L. neivai ventral. 66. L. obscurus ventral. 67. L. ornatus ventral. 68. L. panorpiformis ventral. 69. L. perplexus paratype female, dorsal. Abbreviations: A1, A2 = Anal veins; C = costa; CuA = anterior branch of cubitus; CuP = posterior branch of cubitus; h = humeral crossvein; M1,M2,M4, = branches of the media; r-m = radial-medial crossvein; Rs = radial sector vein; R1, R4, R5 = branches of the radius; Sc = subcosta; sc-r = subcostal-radial crossvein." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
) and the placement of the lateral ocelli approximately their own diameter away from the eye margin and the median ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[376,460,298,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–81" captionStartId="95.[151,263,1524,1547]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-60@95.[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 78–81. Leptomorphus morphology. 78–79. Dorsal view of head showing ocelli placement and arrangement. 78. L. tabatius. 79. L. perplexus. 80–81. Dorsal view of scutum. 80. L. fasciculatus showing covering of fine trichia. 81. L. stigmatus showing pattern and lack of setae or trichia." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,151,2023]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,393,334,359]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">DESCRIPTION</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[408,491,335,359]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Female</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[514,596,335,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–33" captionStartId="89.[151,263,1758,1781]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,223,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-41@89.[151,1436,217,1737]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURES 30–33. Leptomorphus habitus. 30. L. ornatus, female. 31. L. panorpiformis, male. 32. L. perplexus, paratype female. 33. L. quadrimaculatus, male." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[612,675,335,359]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Head</emphasis>
: (
<figureCitation box="[699,781,335,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–81" captionStartId="95.[151,263,1524,1547]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-60@95.[151,1436,193,1503]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 78–81. Leptomorphus morphology. 78–79. Dorsal view of head showing ocelli placement and arrangement. 78. L. tabatius. 79. L. perplexus. 80–81. Dorsal view of scutum. 80. L. fasciculatus showing covering of fine trichia. 81. L. stigmatus showing pattern and lack of setae or trichia." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
) yellow-orange, circular in anterior view. Antenna brown; scape yellow, with yellow setae on entire surface except basal 1/4, anterobasal patch of setulae present; pedicel yellow, with 1–2 large bristles, few setae on apicodorsal margin, patch of fine setae apicoventrally; flagellomere 1 with tapered base yellow remainder brown; flagellomere 6 1.3X as long as broad. Clypeus yellow, circular, strongly protruding; bristles on clypeus light brown, both strong, smaller bristles on entire surface, all directed ventrally, clypeus 2X as long as face. Face yellow; shape a slightly wider than tall triangle, with fine bristles covering face. Frons yellow; with many bristles covering ventral half, frontal furrow running 1/10–1/4 distance from dorsal margin towards ventral margin, frontal cleft faint running to lateral ocellus. Palpus yellow; segment 1 hidden behind eye, segments increasing in length, segment 5 1.5X length of segment 4 with even width from base to apex, segment 3 appears to have large lateral patch of fine yellow setae not clearly delimited and interspersed with dark setae. Labellum yellow. Eye with many long inter-ommatidial setulae (in most inter-ommatidial junctions) on all but medial margin. Occiput yellow with appressed, anteriorly directed setae. Ocelli in a straight line, space between ocelli 1–1.5X diameter of laterals, lateral ocelli 0.5X their own diameter from eye margin, ocellar triangle brown ring around each ocelli but not overlapping other ocelli. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[785,873,803,827]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Thorax</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity box="[975,1074,802,826]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.82" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="1.82">1.82 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[1090,1257,802,826]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.805" metricValueMax="1.89" metricValueMin="1.72" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="1.805" valueMax="1.89" valueMin="1.72">1.72–1.89 mm</quantity>
, n = 4). Yellow. Scutum yellow; surface of scutum covered with small setae; acrostichal setae vaguely present; dorsocentral setae probably present but not clearly distinguishable from other setae; multiple rows of lateral setae present; patch of setae on scutum at wing base present. Scutellum yellow; with 8–10 large bristles and many small bristles. Prescutum yellow. Mediotergite yellow with 22–28 bristles on posterior third, absent. Laterotergite yellow; anterior margin of laterotergite not reaching katepisternum. Anepimeron yellow. Anepisternum yellow. Katepisternum yellow. Antepronotum and proepisternum yellow. Margin of anterior and posterior spiracles yellow with yellow trichia. Metepisternum yellow. Anapleural suture straight and clear. Halter yellow. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1141,1197,1055,1079]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Legs</emphasis>
: principally yellow; extreme anteroapical corner light brown on hind femur, on other femora yellow. Midfemur without apical spine-like process. Tibia with covering of brown macrotrichia, tibial spurs yellow to light brown, foretibial spur length 2.5X apical thickness of foretibia, shortest midtibial spur subequal to length of longest, longest midtibial spur 5X apical thickness of midtibia, shortest hind tibial spur 0.85X length of longest, longest hind tibial spur 5X apical thickness of hind tibia. Foreleg first tarsomere 0.9X length of foretibia. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[841,905,1234,1259]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[921,1005,1234,1258]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–69" captionStartId="93.[151,263,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,181,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-173@93.[176,1420,181,1791]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 56–69. Leptomorphus wings. 56. L. furcatus paratype male, dorsal. 57. L. gracilis, ventral. 58. L. grjebinei, ventral. 59. L. hyalinus, ventral. 60. L. magnificus, ventral. 61. L. mandelai holotype male, ventral. 62. L. medleri, ventral. 63. L. nebulosus dark form, dorsal. Arrow indicates cell r4 (contains an extra vein in this specimen). 64. L. nebulosus light form, dorsal. 65. L. neivai ventral. 66. L. obscurus ventral. 67. L. ornatus ventral. 68. L. panorpiformis ventral. 69. L. perplexus paratype female, dorsal. Abbreviations: A1, A2 = Anal veins; C = costa; CuA = anterior branch of cubitus; CuP = posterior branch of cubitus; h = humeral crossvein; M1,M2,M4, = branches of the media; r-m = radial-medial crossvein; Rs = radial sector vein; R1, R4, R5 = branches of the radius; Sc = subcosta; sc-r = subcostal-radial crossvein." pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
): Length 
<quantity box="[1111,1196,1234,1258]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="6.6">6.6 mm</quantity>
(6.0– 
<quantity box="[1262,1350,1234,1258]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.9" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="6.9">6.9 mm</quantity>
, n = 4). Hyaline; apical macula absent; medial macula absent. Macrotrichia in all cells. Setae on basal posterior margin of wing (along base of cell a) alternating long, short. Calypter with group of macrotrichia. Vein sc-r present, apical end joining R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[256,264,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">1</subScript>
at least 3X its own length after origin of Rs. R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[789,797,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">4</subScript>
present. R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[915,923,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">5</subScript>
slightly sinusoidal. M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1173,1181,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">1</subScript>
reaching apex at same level as R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[266,274,1397,1411]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">5</subScript>
, apices of M veins clearly reaching wing margin. M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[883,891,1397,1411]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">4</subScript>
-CuA fork arising well before origin of r-m. A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,1397,1411]" fontSize="6" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">2</subScript>
present. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[245,361,1420,1445]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tergites principally yellow, T1 light brown. Cercus yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,151,2023]" box="[199,388,1456,1480]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis box="[199,264,1456,1480]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,151,2023]" box="[199,450,1492,1516]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis box="[199,318,1493,1516]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Immatures</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
